Firewalls, and network troubleshooting.

A firewall decides which network packets the kernel accepts and which it drops. On Linux the filter itself lives inside the kernel, in a module called nftables, which supersedes the older iptables. But you don't usually write low-level rules; you drive it through a friendly front-end. On Debian and Ubuntu that's ufw, the uncomplicated firewall; on Red Hat and Fedora it's firewalld.

ufw is default-deny for incoming traffic and default-allow for outgoing. So you allow a service, like sudo ufw allow ssh to open port twenty-two, or ufw allow eighty-slash-tcp by port and protocol, and then sudo ufw enable to turn it on. And here is the single most important warning in this whole module: before you enable ufw on a remote machine, allow SSH first. If you enable a default-deny firewall without allowing port twenty-two, you will instantly lock yourself out of that machine, and it's the classic way people brick their own cloud VMs. firewalld works a little differently, organizing rules into zones per interface, and it has a two-step model: changes are runtime until you add dash-dash-permanent and then dash-dash-reload to make them stick.

Now, troubleshooting, and the key is to work up the layers methodically instead of guessing. Step one: am I even connected? ip dash-b-r addr, do I have an IP address? Step two: can I reach my gateway? ping dash-c four at the gateway. Step three: can I reach the wider internet? ping one dot one dot one dot one, a nice stable address. Step four: is DNS working? Compare dig plus-short against dig at eight dot eight dot eight dot eight plus-short; if only the second one works, your resolver is broken, not the internet. Step five: where does the path die? traceroute the destination. And step six: is the port actually reachable and the service actually listening? From outside, nc dash-z-v against the host and port tests whether you can even open a connection. And on the server itself, ss dash-t-u-n-l-p, the modern replacement for netstat, shows every listening TCP and UDP socket along with which process owns it. If it's still mysterious after all that, step seven is tcpdump, to watch the actual packets on the wire.

So the mental flowchart for "a remote service isn't reachable" is: ping the host, test the port, resolve the name, trace the path, and check the service is actually listening. For the exam, be comfortable with ping, traceroute, ss dash-t-u-n-l-p, dig, nc, and the basics of tcpdump.
